Using Vieta's formulas, the sum of the roots \( r \) and \( s \) is \( -k \) and their product is 36. We need to find all pairs of integers \((r, s)\) such that \( r \cdot s = 36 \) and \( r \neq s \). The pairs of integers whose product is 36 are: \[ (1, 36), (2, 18), (3, 12), (4, 9), (-1, -36), (-2, -18), (-3, -12), (-4, -9) \] For each pair, the sum \( r + s \) gives the value \( -k \). Calculating these sums: \[ 1 + 36 = 37 \implies k = -37 \] \[ 2 + 18 = 20 \implies k = -20 \] \[ 3 + 12 = 15 \implies k = -15 \] \[ 4 + 9 = 13 \implies k = -13 \] \[ -1 + (-36) = -37 \implies k = 37 \] \[ -2 + (-18) = -20 \implies k = 20 \] \[ -3 + (-12) = -15 \implies k = 15 \] \[ -4 + (-9) = -13 \implies k = 13 \] Thus, the distinct values of \( k \) are \( \pm 37, \pm 20, \pm 15, \pm 13 \). This gives us 8 distinct values of \( k \). Therefore, the number of values of \( k \) is \(\boxed{8}\).
